definition.value: An agent that selectively binds to and activates an opioid receptor.
Any chemical substance that acts as an antagonist at the N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor.
Any member of the class of fungicides whose members contain two phenyl (or substituted phenyl) groups attached to a single carbon or heteratom.
A chiral compound used to induce stereoselectivity into a reaction.
An agent which blocks glucagon receptors.
Any compound that inhibits the action of tryptophan synthase.
An enzyme inhibitor, generally irreversible, that is similar in structure to a particular substrate for a specific enzyme.

Any substance that inhibits the action of N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. They tend to induce a state known as dissociative anesthesia, marked by catalepsy, amnesia, and analgesia, while side effects can include hallucinations, nightmares, and confusion. Due to their psychotomimetic effects, many NMDA receptor antagonists are used as recreational drugs.
Any substance which inhibits the action of receptors for excitatory amino acids.
Any substance that possesses little anaesthetic effect by itself, but which enhances or potentiates the anaesthetic action of other drugs when given at the same time.
Any pharmacological or immunological agent that modifies the effect of other agents such as drugs or vaccines while having few if any direct effects when given by itself.
A type of antigen capable on its own of inducing an immune response.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to inhibit or promote polymerisation of microtubules.
Any compound that inhibits the action of riboflavin synthetase.
A poison that interferes with the function of the kidneys.
A hormone antagonist that blocks angiotensin receptors.
A drug used in the treatment of bile or liver disorders.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the function of histone deacetylase (EC 3.5.1.98).
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of inositol phosphorylceramide synthase.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of nitric oxide synthase, EC 1.14.13.39.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to promote polymerisation of microtubules.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to inhibit polymerisation of microtubules.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a metabotropic glutamate receptor.
Any donor that can transfer acyl groups between molecular entities.
Any compound that inhibits the action of glutamate synthase.
A class of secondary metabolites developed by many plants to influence the behaviour, growth or survival of herbivores, and thus acting as a defence against herbivory.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of anaplastic lymphoma kinase.

A molecular messenger in which the molecule is specifically involved in transmitting information between cells. Such molecules are released from the cell sending the signal, cross over the gap between cells by diffusion, and interact with specific receptors in another cell, triggering a response in that cell by activating a series of enzyme controlled reactions which lead to changes inside the cell.
Any inhibitor of sphingosine N-acyltransferase, EC 2.3.1.24.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the function of aconitase.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of phosphonopyruvate hydrolase.
Any inhibitor of phosphoprotein phosphatase, EC 3.1.3.16.
Any additive that enhances the efficiency of fuel.
Any compound that is able to prevent damage to the liver.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates an odorant receptor.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of a poly(ADP-ribose)polymerase.
A compound that inhibits the action of a sialyltransferase.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of cytochrome c oxidase.
An emulsifier used in food manufacturing.
A catalyst that facilitates the migration of a reactant from one phase into another phase where reaction occurs.
Chemical role played by a material when used to promote crystallisation.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of purine nucleoside phosphorylase.
An agonist that binds to and activates sphingosine 1-phosphate receptors.
